docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Senate Democrats on Thursday grilled Ronald D. Vitiello, President Trump’s pick to lead Immigration and Customs Enforcement, bombarding him with pointed questions about the administration’s detention of migrant children and a three-year-old Twitter post in which he made derogatory remarks about the Democratic Party.

headline.main: Democrats Grill ICE Nominee About Child Detentions and a Derogatory Tweet
headline.print_headline: Immigration Pick Grilled About Child Detentions And an Insult on Twitter

docs.abstract: The Department of Homeland Security did not fully consider where barriers were needed or how their cost could vary based on factors like terrain, a Government Accountability Office report says.

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Trump administration could potentially waste billions of dollars on a border wall because it failed to fully account for factors like varying terrain and land ownership along the Southwest border, according to a new report.

headline.main: Trump’s Border Wall Could Waste Billions of Dollars, Report Says
headline.print_headline: Wall’s Costs Likely to Swell, Report Says

docs.abstract: With President Trump’s apparent blessing, lawmakers are considering a one- or two-week spending bill to set aside negotiations until after former President George Bush’s funeral.
docs.snippet: With President Trump’s apparent blessing, lawmakers are considering a one- or two-week spending bill to set aside negotiations until after former President George Bush’s funeral.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Lawmakers were discussing on Sunday a short-term spending bill that would avert the possibility of a partial government shutdown as Washington mourns former President George Bush, according to people familiar with the talks.

headline.main: Lawmakers Discuss Deal to Push Back Shutdown Deadline While Mourning Bush
headline.print_headline: Lawmakers Discuss Deal to Avert a Shutdown While Mourning Bush
